@startuml fig-udp-anycast-simulation
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam roundcorner 12
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Simulated UDP anycast over IPv6 (laboratory setup)

participant "Client\nAF_INET6\ntarget: [::1]:5007" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server S1\nbind [::]:5007\nserver_id = S1" as S1 #C8E6C9
participant "Server S2\nbind [::]:5007\nserver_id = S2" as S2 #ECEFF1

note over C
  In a real anycast deployment
  routing selects the nearest
  server. Here we simulate
  on loopback (::1).
end note

C -[#1565C0]> S1 : "Hello, anycast server!"
S1 -[#43A047]-> C : "[S1] Reply from anycast server"

note over S1
  The kernel delivers the datagram
  to whichever process is bound
  to the address. In a true anycast
  network, BGP or OSPF would choose.
end note

|||

note over S2 #FFEBEE
  S2 does not receive the packet
  in this local simulation because
  both servers share the same host.
end note

legend right
  This laboratory exercise simulates anycast
  on localhost using IPv6 (AF_INET6).
  Real anycast requires identical addresses
  announced from multiple locations via
  routing protocols (BGP, OSPF).
  The network routes to the nearest instance.
endlegend
@enduml
